Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Paynel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Payne","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."]}]},{"name":"Fulk","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fulke","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. The name was originally a short form of various compound names containing the word <i>volk</i> ‘people, tribe’ (compare modern English <i>folk</i>). It has gradually died out of general use, but is still used in certain families, in particular the Grevilles. Fulke Greville, 1st Baron Brooke, was a leading figure at the court of Elizabeth I.  See also  Greville ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":46,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Fulk de Paynel was born in 1060, in Dudley, Staffordshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Beatrix FitzWilliam. He died about 1135, in Dudley, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1060–Abt 1135":"1060–umbes 1135","1064–Female":"1064–Surnud","1070–1160":"1070–1160","1100–1125":"1100–1125","1100–1161":"1100–1161","1098–1165":"1098–1165","1060–1135":"1060–1135","1066":"1066","1165":"1165","1098":"1098","1086":"1086","1064":"1064","1096":"1096","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","Abt 1135":"umbes 1135","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","about 1098":"umbes 1098","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Dudley, Midlands, Leicestershire, England":"Midlands, Leicestershire, England","Dudley, Worcestershire, England":"Dudley, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dudley, Staffordshire, England":"Dudley, Staffordshire, England","Little Crawley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Little Crawley, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1060–Abt 1135":"1060–noin 1135","1064–Female":"1064–Kuollut","1070–1160":"1070–1160","1100–1125":"1100–1125","1100–1161":"1100–1161","1098–1165":"1098–1165","1060–1135":"1060–1135","1066":"1066","1165":"1165","1098":"1098","1086":"1086","1064":"1064","1096":"1096","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","Abt 1135":"noin 1135","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","about 1098":"noin 1098","about 1100":"noin 1100","Dudley, Midlands, Leicestershire, England":"Midlands, Leicestershire, England","Dudley, Worcestershire, England":"Dudley, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dudley, Staffordshire, England":"Dudley, Staffordshire, England","Little Crawley, Buckinghamshire, England":"Little Crawley, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1060–Abt 1135":"106